99
00:07:53,348 --> 00:07:54,388
Objection.

100
00:07:54,474 --> 00:07:55,524
Sustained.

101
00:07:55,601 --> 00:07:59,561
The jury will disregard the last
remark about the defendant's desire,

102
00:07:59,646 --> 00:08:01,316
which is speculation.

103
00:08:01,398 --> 00:08:04,108
And so, on April 12,

104
00:08:04,193 --> 00:08:07,823
the defendant walked into
the woods of Cold Spring Park

105
00:08:07,905 --> 00:08:12,025
with a knife in his pocket
and an idea in his mind.

106
00:08:13,035 --> 00:08:16,905
Did he ambush the victim, or
were there words exchanged first?

107
00:08:18,207 --> 00:08:21,667
Maybe Ben called him a name.

108
00:08:22,669 --> 00:08:24,339
Or even threatened him.

109
00:08:25,464 --> 00:08:26,724
We don't know.

110
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:30,085
All we know

111
00:08:30,177 --> 00:08:35,967
is that the defendant punched his
knife three times into Ben Rifkin's chest,

112
00:08:36,850 --> 00:08:38,140
killing him.

113
00:08:40,062 --> 00:08:41,692
Three...

114
00:08:42,773 --> 00:08:46,533
evenly spaced wounds.

115
00:08:49,363 --> 00:08:50,363
One.

116
00:08:52,449 --> 00:08:53,449
Two.

117
00:08:55,494 --> 00:08:56,754
Three.

118
00:08:59,623 --> 00:09:05,423
You see a tragedy as enormous
as this, and it makes you furious.

119
00:09:06,296 --> 00:09:08,586
You want someone to pay.

120
00:09:09,216 --> 00:09:10,966
I do too. I do.

121
00:09:12,219 --> 00:09:13,639
It's only human.

122
00:09:15,222 --> 00:09:19,062
But Jacob Barber is innocent.

123
00:09:20,227 --> 00:09:24,607
And I want to say that again so
that there is no misunderstanding.

124
00:09:25,274 --> 00:09:30,574
Jacob Barber is wholly
and completely innocent.

125
00:09:32,072 --> 00:09:35,952
When you understand what
really happened that day,

126
00:09:36,910 --> 00:09:41,790
you'll see this case for what
it is... a rush to judgment.

127
00:09:43,125 --> 00:09:45,085
The fingerprint, for example,

128
00:09:45,169 --> 00:09:47,459
that the prosecution
made such a big deal about,

129
00:09:47,546 --> 00:09:49,756
you're going to hear
how that print got there,

130
00:09:49,840 --> 00:09:53,260
just as Jacob told the police
officer who arrested him

131
00:09:53,343 --> 00:09:55,263
the moment that he was asked.

132
00:09:56,430 --> 00:10:00,480
He saw his classmate lying on
the ground, and he tried to help.

133
00:10:01,393 --> 00:10:07,273
And when he discovered that Ben was
dead, saw all that blood, he panicked.

134
00:10:07,357 --> 00:10:12,277
He feared that if he told someone
about the body, he'd become a suspect.

135
00:10:12,362 --> 00:10:16,242
After all, this was Ben
Rifkin, the boy who bullied him.

136
00:10:16,325 --> 00:10:19,325
Everyone knew that. How would it look?

137
00:10:20,537 --> 00:10:26,497
Does Jacob wish that he had been
braver from the start and told the truth?

138
00:10:27,419 --> 00:10:29,129
Of course he does.

139
00:10:29,213 --> 00:10:33,803
It was the worst mistake he's ever made.
It was a horrible, terrifying mistake.

140
00:10:35,302 --> 00:10:36,972
But he was a boy.

141
00:10:38,138 --> 00:10:41,388
And I don't give a damn how
the state chooses to try him.

142
00:10:41,475 --> 00:10:44,685
He was a 14-year-old boy.

143
00:10:46,104 --> 00:10:48,154
And boys make mistakes.

144
00:10:50,734 --> 00:10:52,534
But we are adults...

145
00:10:54,071 --> 00:10:57,071
with a grave responsibility before us.

146
00:10:58,200 --> 00:10:59,950
A child is dead.

147
00:11:01,370 --> 00:11:04,870
Don't destroy another
child's life to make up for it.

148
00:11:06,041 --> 00:11:07,671
That isn't justice.

149
00:11:09,628 --> 00:11:11,418
That's just another tragedy.

